# Git worktrees and parallel work

For **multiple Cursor/agent sessions**, **large migrations**, or **several experimental branches at once**, prefer **one git worktree per parallel line of work** instead of many agents editing the same checkout.

## When to use worktrees

- Parallel refactors (e.g. deer-flow backend vs. monument scripts).
- Long-running experiments while `main` stays clean for small fixes.
- Multiple agents or terminals that would otherwise conflict on the same working tree.

## Where to read the full playbook

Commands, naming, cleanup, and agent-lab-oriented examples: **`docs/GIT_WORKTREES_PARALLEL_AGENTS.md`**.

## Quick pattern

```bash
# From agent-lab repo root (example)
git fetch origin
git worktree add ../agent-lab-wt-deerflow -b experiment/deerflow-async origin/main
```

Worktrees can also live under a ignored path such as `.git-worktrees/<name>/` if you prefer them inside the tree; see the doc for tradeoffs.
